article.description:
Dirk Nowitzki had 25 points and Nick Van Exel
scored 24 against his former team to help the Dallas Mavericks beat
Denver 108-96 Monday night, completing their second straight
season-series sweep of the Nuggets.
article.headline: Mavs sweep season series for second straight year
article.linkText: Nowitzki, Mavs continue success against Nuggets
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Nick Van Exel expects to be booed when he plays in Denver. But he isn't about to let it get under his skin.
Nowitzki

Van Exel

Dirk Nowitzki scored 25 points and Van Exel had 24 against his former team to help the Dallas Mavericks beat Denver 108-96 Monday night, completing their second straight season sweep of the Nuggets. Nowitzki overcame a 6-for-23 shooting night by going 12-of-12 from the line. Van Exel, who played nearly four season with the Nuggets, was soundly booed throughout the game. He made two layups in the final two minutes. "I never look forward to coming here, especially when I know I am going to get booed,'' Van Exel said. "It's suppose to bother me, but I'm not really worried about the fans. We got the win and that was the most important thing.'' It was the eighth straight win over Denver for the Mavericks, who increased their lead over idle San Antonio to 3½ games in the Midwest Division. "I thought Nick responded well to the boos,'' Dallas coach Don Nelson said of Van Exel, who reached double figures for the 35th time this season. "We needed Nick to come on big and score, and he did.'' Juwan Howard had 25 points and Nene Hilario had 23 for Denver. Rodney White added 17 points, 12 rebounds and 10 assists for his first career triple-double. "That was a nice effort by Rodney, who has worked hard over the past couple of weeks,'' Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "I can't say the same about our transition defense in the first half, and our inability to handle the basketball and shoot free throws.'' Denver allowed 20 points on fast breaks in the first two quarters. The Nuggets further hurt themselves with 17 turnovers and 64 percent shooting from the line. After allowing 68 points in the first half, the Nuggets held Dallas to 8-for-23 shooting in the third quarter, including an 0-for-7 performance by Nowitzki. While Dallas struggled, Hilario converted two dunks on breaks during a 6-0 run to get Denver to 71-60. Denver's Shammond Williams hit a 3-pointer with 3:15 left in the third to cut Dallas' lead to nine, 79-70, before Van Exel's layup gave the Mavericks a double-digit lead heading into the fourth. "We couldn't make any shots,'' Nowitzki said. "They have been giving us fits all year, and we were fortunate to beat them all four times.'' Shawn Bradley's layup between two defenders two minutes into the fourth quarter put the Mavericks up 89-76, but Donnell Harvey's dunk at the end of a 5-0 run narrowed the lead to 89-81. Dallas got the lead back to 96-94 on Van Exel's layup and a 3-pointer by Steve Nash with 5:50 left. Howard's jumper got Denver to 98-89 with 4:06, but the Nuggets never got closer. Hilario hit two free throws, but Van Exel converted the two layups as the crowd booed. "I put the ball in Nick's hands at the end, because Dirk wasn't making many outside shots,'' Nelson said. "Nick found a way to penetrate and make some holes for himself.'' Game notes
Michael Finley was in street clothes for the second straight game with a strained left hamstring. ... Dallas guard Avery Johnson celebrated his 38th birthday. ... Denver last beat Dallas on Jan. 27, 2001 in Denver. ... Adam Harrington becomes the sixth rookie on Denver's roster when he signed a 10-day contract Sunday. ... The Nuggets chose to shut down Ryan Bowen for the remainder of the season because of the strained abdominal muscle that troubled him the past three weeks.
